<subSubSection lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="516" pageId="14" pageNumber="515" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,1430,2031]" lastBlockId="15.[151,1437,151,573]" lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="516" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1970,1995]" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Females of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Mello-Leitao" baseAuthorityYear="1929" box="[469,622,1970,1995]" class="Arachnida" family="Thomisidae" genus="Epicadus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="14" pageNumber="515" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pustulosus">
<emphasis box="[469,622,1970,1995]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">E. pustulosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are very similar to those of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Mello-Leitao" baseAuthorityYear="1929" box="[963,1099,1970,1995]" class="Arachnida" family="Thomisidae" genus="Epicadus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="14" pageNumber="515" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caudatus">
<emphasis box="[963,1099,1970,1995]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">E. caudatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in their cryptic bark-dweller habitus with rugose tegument and predominant dark-brown coloration. Both species also share squared leg segments and protuberant anterior femora suffused with many conical tubercles. However, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Mello-Leitao" baseAuthorityYear="1929" box="[1200,1351,151,176]" class="Arachnida" family="Thomisidae" genus="Epicadus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pustulosus">
<emphasis box="[1200,1351,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">E. pustulosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by the yellow blister-shaped sockets on the ventral surface of femora I and II and by the anterior projection on the epigynal plate, which covers the copulatory openings entirely. Males can be easily recognized by their equal-sized, short and spiniform opisthosomal projections, by a basal indentation on the DTA and by its curvature (pointing to the dorsum of the cymbium).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
